31:11.303 --> 31:23.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now: a major
agreement on ocean
conservation today.

31:23.348 --> 31:28.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dozens of nations created the
world's largest
marine reserve at the bottom of
the globe.

31:28.720 --> 31:30.522 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
William Brangham has the story.

31:30.555 --> 31:35.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Twenty-four
countries and
the European Union agreed today
to set aside

31:35.227 --> 31:38.430 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
600,000 square miles of ocean.

31:38.463 --> 31:42.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The newly protected zone is in
the Ross Sea,
which borders Antarctica.

31:42.601 --> 31:45.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Most commercial fishing will be
banned in
this area, though researchers
will be allowed

31:45.904 --> 31:47.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to take limited samples.

31:47.706 --> 31:53.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The protection will take effect
starting December
2017, and will continue for 35
years.

31:53.445 --> 31:57.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on what this means, and
how it came
to be, I am joined by Karen
Sack.

31:57.949 --> 32:01.319 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's managing director of
conservation organization
Ocean Unite.

32:01.353 --> 32:02.521 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Welcome.

32:02.554 --> 32:03.755 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KAREN SACK, Managing Director,
Ocean Unite:
Thank you.

32:03.789 --> 32:05.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Nice to be
reporting on
some good news.

32:05.724 --> 32:10.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAREN SACK: It's fantastic to be
talking about
some really unprecedented news
for the ocean.

32:10.562 --> 32:12.464 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Tell us, how
important is
this?

32:12.497 --> 32:18.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAREN SACK: This is truly a
seminal event
in international ocean
governance.

32:18.370 --> 32:23.775 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's the first time that
countries around
the world are coming together to
agree not

32:23.809 --> 32:29.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to take fish or other species
out of the water,
but to leave them in, and to
leave them in

32:29.314 --> 32:31.149 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for a good long period of time.

32:31.183 --> 32:35.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, what
species in particular
are we protecting here with this
preserve?

32:35.420 --> 32:42.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAREN SACK: Well, the Ross Sea
is known as
a Garden of Eden in the ocean,
or sometimes

32:42.360 --> 32:44.362 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
called the ocean's Serengeti.

32:44.396 --> 32:52.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are 16,000 species that
live there,
from seals, whales, penguins, of
course.

32:52.037 --> 32:58.977 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Commercially, the species that
is caught there
is called Antarctic toothfish.

32:59.010 --> 33:01.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's known in the United States
as Chilean
sea bass.

33:01.613 --> 33:06.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, when we
think of these
preserves normally being done,
we think of

33:06.117 --> 33:10.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
them being done by individual
nations within
their own territorial waters.

33:10.989 --> 33:12.491 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But this one is quite different.

33:12.524 --> 33:14.292 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KAREN SACK: It is.

33:14.326 --> 33:20.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's because the Antarctic and
the Southern
Ocean around it is governed
collectively by

33:20.265 --> 33:23.869 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a group of countries under the
Antarctic Treaty
System.

33:23.902 --> 33:28.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the system actually came
into being at
the height of the Cold War,
where countries

33:28.106 --> 33:32.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
set aside their differences and
agreed to
govern the Antarctic as a place
for peace

33:32.544 --> 33:33.879 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and science.

33:33.912 --> 33:39.084 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That governance is now extending
into the
ocean.

33:39.117 --> 33:45.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And about five years ago, the
countries agreed
to begin to work together to
establish marine

33:45.290 --> 33:47.525 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
reserves and protected areas.

33:47.559 --> 33:51.129 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the Ross Sea is the first
big one that
they have managed to agree to.

33:51.162 --> 33:56.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I understand
also that Russia
needed to be cajoled to putting
its name on

33:56.635 --> 33:58.436 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this agreement.

33:58.470 --> 34:02.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAREN SACK: Well, part of the
difficulty and
why this is such a significant
agreement is

34:02.574 --> 34:08.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that decisions are made by
consensus, which
means that all of those 24
countries and the

34:08.480 --> 34:13.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
European Union have to agree to
a decision
going forward.

34:14.019 --> 34:23.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For several years, Russia and
China were not
supportive of establishing a
protective area.

34:23.094 --> 34:27.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There was very high-level
engagement from
the Obama administration.

34:27.332 --> 34:34.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We believe that President Obama
actually discussed
this issue with President Xi in
China, and

34:35.006 --> 34:37.175 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that shifted the Chinese
position.

34:37.208 --> 34:45.817 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Over the last 18 months,
Secretary Kerry has
really worked incredibly hard
with his counterparts

34:45.850 --> 34:51.323 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in New Zealand and around the
world, working
with Minister Lavrov of Russia.

34:51.356 --> 34:56.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was just earlier this
week, we understand,
that we managed to reach
agreement on this

34:56.828 --> 34:57.796 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
issue.

34:57.829 --> 34:58.797 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It was that
touch and go?

34:58.830 --> 35:01.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KAREN SACK: It was that close.

35:01.900 --> 35:07.372 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Several of us were planning for
maybe another
year of negotiation.

35:07.405 --> 35:13.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it is just fantastic that we
managed to
get to this point, and is a
testament to the

35:13.912 --> 35:21.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ability of multinationalism to
work, even
when there are incredibly
difficult issues

35:21.219 --> 35:22.921 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the global agenda at the
moment.

35:22.954 --> 35:27.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: We said at the
beginning
this is a 35-year period of time
where this

35:27.459 --> 35:28.526 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
space will be protected.

35:28.560 --> 35:30.195 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is that long enough?

35:30.228 --> 35:32.263 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KAREN SACK: Well, no, it isn't.

35:32.297 --> 35:37.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in fact, this was one of
the big sticking
points for Russia, how long the
area should

35:37.669 --> 35:39.471 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
be protected for.

35:39.504 --> 35:46.378 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The science shows that
marine-protected areas
should be in place without a
limit in their

35:46.411 --> 35:48.246 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
duration.

35:48.279 --> 35:53.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We believe, though, that these
35 years will
provide the marine life in the
Antarctic and

35:53.952 --> 36:03.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Ross Sea area the ability to
show us all
just how amazing it is and will
convince everyone

36:03.595 --> 36:10.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sitting at that table 35 years
from now to
continue protecting this
unbelievably iconic

36:10.535 --> 36:12.337 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and special ocean area.

36:12.370 --> 36:16.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Karen Sack, thank
you so much for being here.

36:16.374 --> 36:22.547 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KAREN SACK: Thank you.

