49:06.610 --> 49:09.513 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, finally, a "NewsHour"
Essay.

49:09.547 --> 49:14.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As we just discussed, this
presidential campaign
has raised a lot of questions
about how women

49:14.451 --> 49:16.687 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
are seen and discussed.

49:16.720 --> 49:21.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the end of the first debate,
Hillary Clinton
mentioned former Miss Universe
Alicia Machado.

49:21.659 --> 49:27.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
During her reign, pageant owner
Donald Trump
repeatedly commented on Machado
for gaining

49:28.032 --> 49:32.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
weight, just one example of size
consciousness
in our society.

49:32.436 --> 49:37.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tonight, fashion guru Tim Gunn
shares a challenge
for American designers.

49:37.608 --> 49:41.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIM GUNN, Fashion Consultant: To
begin, I
love the American fashion
industry, but it

49:41.645 --> 49:43.581 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
has a lot of problems.

49:43.614 --> 49:48.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Consider this: When the actress
Leslie Jones
couldn't find anything to wear
to her "Ghostbusters"

49:48.552 --> 49:53.324 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
premiere, she had to call out on
social media
to find someone to dress her.

49:53.357 --> 49:55.125 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How did that happen?

49:55.159 --> 50:00.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Would it surprise you to know
that the average
American woman now wears between
a size 16

50:00.464 --> 50:02.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and a size 18?

50:02.199 --> 50:07.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She is what the industry calls a
plus-size
woman, a term that I would like
to erase.

50:07.605 --> 50:12.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are more than 80 million
of these women
in America, and for the past
three years,

50:12.343 --> 50:17.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they have increased their
spending on clothes
faster than their straight-size
counterparts.

50:17.815 --> 50:20.751 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But many designers refuse to
make clothes
for them.

50:20.784 --> 50:23.053 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They pretend that they don't
even exist.

50:23.087 --> 50:28.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have spoken to many people in
the industry
about this, and the overwhelming
response

50:28.359 --> 50:31.595 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is, "I'm not interested in her."

50:31.629 --> 50:37.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They say the plus-size woman is
complicated,
different and difficult, and
that no two size

50:37.334 --> 50:39.703 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
16s are alike.

50:39.737 --> 50:41.372 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Let's decode that.

50:41.405 --> 50:45.409 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The fashion industry works from
standards
established decades ago.

50:45.442 --> 50:47.244 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Habits are hard to break.

50:47.278 --> 50:52.116 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From the runway, to magazines,
pictures of
how clothes are supposed to
look, how women

50:52.149 --> 50:54.752 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are supposed to look, are set.

50:54.785 --> 50:57.421 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it all revolves around
thinness.

50:57.454 --> 51:03.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For decades, models have trotted
down the
runway with bodies that are
completely unattainable

51:03.761 --> 51:05.095 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for most women.

51:05.129 --> 51:09.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yet we have been conditioned to
think that
that's what looks good.

51:09.133 --> 51:13.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is no reason why larger
women can't
look just as fabulous as all
other women.

51:13.837 --> 51:17.041 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's a design issue, and not a
customer issue.

51:17.074 --> 51:22.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The key is the following: It's
the harmonious
balance of silhouette,
proportion and fit.

51:22.546 --> 51:28.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Right now, most plus-size
designs make the
body look larger, with box
pleats and shoulder

51:28.052 --> 51:29.019 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
pads.

51:29.053 --> 51:31.388 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Trust that I'm not trivializing
the task.

51:31.422 --> 51:33.157 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's challenging.

51:33.190 --> 51:36.393 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Designs need to be reconceived,
not just sized
up.

51:36.427 --> 51:40.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And done right, our clothing can
create an
optical illusion that helps us
look taller

51:40.664 --> 51:41.932 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and slimmer.

51:41.966 --> 51:46.670 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, done wrong, we look worse
than if we
were, well, naked.

51:46.704 --> 51:50.007 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Plus-size women deserve fashion,
and they
deserve choices.

51:50.040 --> 51:54.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm not looking for solutions
from high-end
designers, because it's a given
that they

51:54.812 --> 51:59.883 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
don't want their precious brands
tarnished
by the likes of a size 16.

51:59.917 --> 52:03.253 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
This message is for more
accessible designers.

52:03.287 --> 52:05.856 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's time to step up to the
plate.

52:05.889 --> 52:09.526 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Furthermore, why aren't
retailers demanding
that this be done?

52:09.560 --> 52:13.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The retailers have plenty of
leverage, as
in: Marc Jacobs, if you want to
continue to

52:13.931 --> 52:18.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
own the current space that you
have in our
store, then we also need
clothing for our

52:18.469 --> 52:24.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
larger market; 14-plus is now
the shape of
women in this nation, and
designers need to

52:24.508 --> 52:27.177 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
wrap their creative minds around
that.

52:27.211 --> 52:32.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I profoundly believe that women
of every size
can look great.

52:32.483 --> 52:37.554 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And in this time of
inclusiveness, why should
80 million women be
marginalized?

52:37.588 --> 52:40.024 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Designers, make it work.

52:40.057 --> 52:42.493 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Hear, hear.

52:42.526 --> 52:44.561 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's about time.

